ue:**\n| Period | Launch Services | Launch & Development | Total Space |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Q1 2026** (Three Months Ended Mar 31) | 53.3% | 46.7% | 100.0% |\n| **Q1 2025** (Three Months Ended Mar 31) | 65.4% | 34.6% | 100.0% |\n| **FY 2025** (Year Ended Dec 31) | 63.0% | 37.0% | 100.0% |\n| **FY 2024** (Year Ended Dec 31) | 68.2% | 31.8% | 100.0% |\n| **FY 2023** (Year Ended Dec 31) | 55.2% | 44.8% | 100.0% |\n\n**Absolute Revenue Figures (in Millions):**\n| Period | Launch Services | Launch & Development | Total Space Revenue |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Q1 2026** | $330 | $289 | **$619** |\n| **Q1 2025** | $566 | $299 | **$865** |\n| **FY 2025** | $2,576 | $1,510 | **$4,086** |\n| **FY 2024** | $2,584 | $1,212 | **$3,796** |\n| **FY 2023** | $1,964 | $1,593 | **$3,557** |\n\n### 3. Growth Expectations and Capacity Allocation\nThe company's strategic focus on internal infrastructure heavily dictates the financial trajectory of the Space segment:\n\n*   **Subordinated External Growth:** Space revenue growth is expected to continue to be **lower than total company revenue growth**. This is because the company's internal businesses are absorbing most of the growth in launch capacity.\n*   **Connectivity & AI Capacity Allocation:** The company allocates a significant amount of launch capacity to its Connectivity segment (Starlink) and expects to allocate a significant amount to its **AI segment** in the future. Because these are internal deployments, they act as a drag on Space segment top-line revenue growth but serve as the backbone for the company's broader, high-margin recurring revenue ecosystems.\n*   **Shift Toward Development Contracts:** Management expects **Launch and Development** to represent a larger portion of Space revenue in the future as the company continues to execute and serve long-term contracts for government customers. \n*   **Period-to-Period Volatility:** Space revenue will naturally vary from period to period based on